    "contenu": "### Text content from the document \"Sugar Candies and Confectionery\":\n\n---\n\n**How Sugar Crystals Form**\nSugar molecules have a natural tendency to bond to each other in orderly arrays and form dense solid masses, or crystals. When sugar crystals are dissolved in water to make a syrup, the water molecules overcome that tendency by forming their own bonds with the sugar molecules, surrounding and separating them from each other. If the dissolved sugar molecules in a syrup get too crowded for the water molecules to keep the sugars apart from each other, the sugars will begin to bond to each other again and form crystals.\n\n**When Sugar Becomes Supersaturated**\nWhen the syrup contains high levels of dissolved sugar and is then cooled, it can temporarily hold more sugar in solution than it could at normal temperatures, becoming supersaturated. This occurs because the cooling process reduces the sugar's mobility, making it less likely to spontaneously form crystals despite the solution’s high sugar concentration.\n\n**Seed Crystals and Growth**\nAfter a syrup becomes supersaturated, any minor disturbance can cause seed crystals to form, rapidly growing into larger sugar crystals. If these crystals are left undisturbed, they can lead to the formation of large, monolithic sugar masses.\n\n**Candy Texture and Crystal Size**\nWhen making candy, controlling the formation of sugar crystals is essential. Quick cooling or minimal disturbance can promote smaller, more homogenous crystal formation, resulting in a smooth, fine-textured candy. Slower cooling or disturbances can cause larger, discrete crystal formations, producing candy with a coarse texture.\n\n**Degrees of Saturation:**\n1. **Saturated:** The dissolved sugars are at equilibrium with their ability to dissolve further, typically achieved at higher temperatures.\n2. **Supersaturated:** Contains more dissolved sugars than can normally be dissolved at a given temperature, frequently induced by rapidly cooling a hot, saturated sugar solution.\n\n**Crystal Growth and Candy Texture**\nDepending on how a syrup is managed after reaching a supersaturated state, the resultant candy's texture can vary:\n- **Fine texture:** Achieved by fast cooling, which prevents the formation of large crystals.\n- **Coarse texture:** Results from slower cooling or disturbances, allowing large crystals to form.\n\n---\n\n### Visuals in the document:\n\n**Images Description:**\nThe document includes a diagram illustrating how sugar molecules arrange into crystals as syrup cools:\n- **Left:** Shows tightly organized, dense sugar crystals.\n- **Center:** Depicts conditions with many small seed crystals leading to fine-textured candy.\n- **Right:** Illustrates fewer seed crystals, resulting in larger crystals and coarse-textured candy. \n\nEach section of the diagram is labeled to indicate the texture outcome based on the crystallization process, highlighting how different cooling rates and seed crystal sizes affect the final texture of the candy."
