    "contenu": "The document titled \"A SURVEY OF COMMON HERBS\" discusses various herbs, providing insights into their history, characteristics, and culinary uses. Here's an outline of the document's main content:\n\n**Herb Descriptions:**\n\n- **Horehound (Marrubium vulgare)**: Known for its hairy, white leaves and bitter flavor, traditionally used more in candies than cooking.\n  \n- **Hyssop (Hyssopus officinalis)**: Described as a spider-mannered European herb with fresh-mildy and camphor notes, used in ancient Rome and now commonly in Thai and Vietnamese cooking. It influences the flavors of several alcohols.\n\n- **Lavender (Lavandula spp.)**: A Mediterranean plant valued for its floral-woody perfume. Although used more in soaps and candles, its dried blossoms are also a culinary ingredient especially in mixtures like herbes de provence.\n\n- **Lemon Balm (Melissa officinalis)**: An Old World species known for its aroma derived from citronellal and citral, typically paired with fruit dishes and sweets.\n  \n- **Marjoram (Origanum majorana)**: Once classified close to oregano but noted for its less forceful flavor and more floral notes, making it a preferred component in many herb blends for dishes.\n\n- **Mints**: Identified as mostly small plants from damp habitats in Europe, contributing to various culinary preparations.\n\n**Table of Herbs from the Mint Family:**\n\n```markdown\n| Herb       | Scientific Name                 |\n|------------|---------------------------------|\n| Basil      | Ocimum basilicum                |\n| Bergamot   | Monarda didyma                  |\n| Horehound  | Marrubium vulgare               |\n| Hyssop     | Hyssopus officinalis            |\n| Lavender   | Lavandula dentata, L. angustifolia |\n| Lemon balm | Melissa officinalis             |\n| Marjoram   | Origanum majorana               |\n| Mints      | Mentha species                  |\n| Oregano    | Origanum species                |\n| Perilla    | Perilla frutescens  