    "contenu": "The document provided appears to be an excerpt from a book or a comprehensive article discussing various aspects of breads. Here's a structured breakdown of the content:\n\n### Heading: BREADS\n\n---\n\n#### Subheading: Bread Flavor\n\n**Content Summary:**\nThe flavor of simple wheat bread has three main sources:\n1. **Flavor of Wheat Flour**:\n   - Products of yeast and bacterial fermentation.\n   - Reactions caused by oven heat during baking.\n   - Dominant flavors such as vanilla, spicy, metallic, and fatty notes from vanilla, a furanone, and fatty aldehydes.\n   - Richer flavors in whole meal flour including cucumber, fried, “sweaty,” and honey notes.\n\n2. **Yeast Fermentation**:\n   - Generates a “yeasty” character, largely part of which comes from fruity esters and eggy sulfur compounds.\n\n3. **Baking Contributions**:\n   - Baking contributes toasty compounds from browning reactions.\n   - Starters add general complexity and a distinctive sour note from acetic and other organic acids.\n\n#### Subheading: Mass-Produced Breads\n\n**Content Summary:**\n- Process of making commercial breads.\n  - Involves ordinary mixing, kneading, and fermentation.\n  - Utilizes high-powered mechanical dough developers and chemical maturing agents (oxidizers) which can produce a “ripe\" dough in four minutes.\n- **Proofing and Baking**:\n  - Yeast added to such doughs enhances flavor and aeration.\n  - Loaves are briefly proofed and then baked in a tunnel-like metal oven.\n  - Results in a very fine, cake-like texture due to the efficiency of the machines.\n\n#### Subheading: A Scientific Definition of Bread Quality\n\n**Reference Mention**: Raymond Calvel, a noted figure in baking from postwar France.\n\n**Quality Indicators for Bread**:\n- A creamy white crumb indicates proper oxidation and minimal excessive mixing.\n- Distinctive aromas leading to a good bread quality:\n  - Wheat flour scent.\n  - Wheat germ oil aroma.\n  - Hazelnut aroma from the germ.\n  - Aromas from alcoholic dough fermentation.\n  - Caramelization and crust baking.\n- **Preferred Texture Attributes**:\n  - Open grain.\n  - Large gas cells.\n  - Thin-walled cells with a lightly pearlescent appearance, reflecting a high quality French bread.\n\n**Quote Source**: Quoted from \"The Taste of Bread\", translated by R. L. Wirtz.\n\n---\n\nThis content primarily discusses the unique attributes of different breads, the scientific basis of bread quality, and contrasts between home-made and mass-produced breads."
