    "contenu": "The document describes different types of cocktail shakers, focusing on their designs, uses, and the preferences of bartenders. The contents can be summarized structured content:\n\n### Cobblers Shakers:\n- **Description**: A three-piece design dating back to the late nineteenth century, consisting of a large metal tin, a tapered top with a built-in strainer, and a cap.\n- **Advantages**: Acts as an all-in-one cocktail device.\n- **Preferred by**: Many top bartenders.\n- **Disadvantages**:\n  - Creates a vacuum when cocktail volume contracts, making the cap hard to remove.\n  - The built-in strainer doesn't have an adjustable tab, limiting control over the texture of the drink.\n  - It doesn't effectively block ice chips, citrus pulp, and other solids.\n  \n### Parisian Shakers:\n- **Description**: Comprised of two stainless steel tins that create an almost seamless seal.\n- **Advantages**:\n  - Fewer rough edges inside the shaker, reducing chipping of the ice.\n- **Disadvantages**:\n  - Not ideal for busy bar service due to the need for using two hands unless one has very large hands.\n  - Can only shake one cocktail at a time.\n- **Trivia**: Known as “continental shakers” in Paris.\n\n### 18-28 Set:\n- **Description**: Consists of two weighted stainless steel tins, one small (18 ounces) and one large (28 ounces), with some preferring a 30-ounce tin for the larger size.\n- **Usage**: Referred to as the workhorse shaker, suggesting reliable and frequent utility in cocktail making. \n\nThe document includes an image showing three types of shakers from left to right: Boston shaker, 18-28 set, cobbler shaker, and Parisian shaker."
