    "contenu": "The document provides detailed information on the preparation and variations of sauces, particularly focusing on hollandaise, béarnaise, and alternative oil emulsions. Here’s a breakdown of the content:\n\n### Making Hollandaise and Béarnaise\n- **Overview**: It discusses at least five different ways to make hollandaise and béarnaise, each with its pros and cons.\n  \n- **Methods**:\n  - **Carême’s method**: \n    - Start by cooking egg and water-based ingredients until thick.\n    - Whisk in parts of whole butter to emulsify.\n    - Note: It’s easily overcooked due to the small volume of the egg mixture.\n  \n  - **Escoffier’s method**: \n    - Begin by warming yolks and water-based ingredients.\n    - Add either whole or clarified butter.\n    - Cook until the desired consistency is reached with direct heat control.\n\n- **Simple method**:\n  - Ingredients are combined in a saucepan, heated gently until the butter melts and incorporates into the eggs.\n\n- **No-cook yolk method**:\n  - Yolks are not cooked; instead, heated with other ingredients and then combined with clarified butter.\n\n- **Butter-sauce version of a sabayon**:\n  - Incorporate melted or clarified butter and lemon juice or acid into beaten egg yolks.\n\n### Alternative Oil Emulsions\n- **Historical context**: Previously, mayonnaise wasn't just egg-emulsified; there were variations using different stabilizers and flavoring components.\n  \n- **Variations**:\n  - **Magnonnaise blanche**: Uses yolks, possibly with starch or béchamel and meat or bone extract.\n  - **Italian salsa verde**: A mix of hard-boiled egg yolk, garlic, anchovies, and bread emulsified with olive oil.\n  - **Provençal aioli and Greek skordalia**: Use garlic and bread or cooked potatoes for emulsification, typically done in the presence of less oil.\n\nThe document also touches on the challenges and nuances of achieving the right emulsification and consistency in sauces, explaining how different ingredients and techniques can influence the outcome."
