    "source": "396118758-Understanding-Wines-Explaining-Style-and-Quality.pdf_page_88",
    "contenu": "The provided document discusses Bordeaux wines, focusing on aging and classification systems, as well as details on specific wine varieties and regional wines.\n\n1. **Aging and Usage of Barriques:**\n   - Bordeaux wines, mainly the top-quality ones, age exceptionally well due to the use of 225-liter oak barrels called barriques.\n   - New casks might be used for premium wines, impacting the wine's ability to age and its potential oak flavoring.\n\n2. **White Wine Varieties:**\n   - **Sémillon**: Preferred for sweet wines due to its thin skin and affinity for noble rot; often blended with Sauvignon Blanc.\n   - **Sauvignon Blanc**: Contributes to both dry and sweet wines, appreciated for its bright citrus and green fruit aromas, increasingly pivotal in Bordeaux wine blends.\n   - **Muscadelle**: Enhances the floral and sweet qualities of Bordeaux wines, though less common.\n\n3. **Bordeaux Classification Systems:**\n   - The system doesn't classify individual vineyards or plots but the estates or châteaux themselves. The name \"château\" reflects more of a branding term than specific vineyard differentiation.\n   - **Médoc and Sauternes Classification**: Initiated in 1855, listing châteaux in various rank tiers, such as cru bourgeois and cru classé with specific estates like Château Rothschild and Château Latour mentioned.\n   - **Graves (Pessac-Léognan)**: No ranking system, just a classification of all their listed wines.\n   - **Saint-Émilion Grand Cru**: It has an internal classification system, spearheading distinctions among its best vineyards and providing possible promotion or demotion every ten years.\n\n4. **Regions and Wines:**\n   - Bordeaux wines originate where the Dordogne and Garonne rivers meet, dividing into left and right banks each with unique wine profiles (e.g., Médoc and Graves on the Left Bank, and Saint-Émilion on the Right Bank).\n   - The document also briefly mentions the possibility of deep, concentrated flavors from wines matured in new oak barrels and infection by noble rot influencing sweet wine production.\n\nThe information provided is educational, targeting readers interested in the classification and variety nuances of Bordeaux wines."
