    "source": "the-elements-of-taste.pdf_page_83",
    "contenu": "The document provides recipes for preparing \"Mussels and Sauce\", \"Halibut\", and a \"Topping\". Below is the structured content extracted from the document:\n\n---\n\n### MUSSELS AND SAUCE\n- **Ingredients:**\n  - 1 tablespoon butter\n  - 2 tablespoons finely diced spring onions (or scallions)\n  - 2 dozen mussels\n  - 1 cup white wine\n  - Kosher salt\n  - Freshly ground white pepper\n  - 1½-2 cups watercress broth\n\n- **Instructions:**\n  1. Melt the butter in a large pot over medium-high heat.\n  2. Add the onions and cook until soft and translucent.\n  3. Add the mussels and wine and season with salt and pepper.\n  4. Cover the pot, increase the heat to high, and cook until the mussels open, usually less than 5 minutes. Drain the mussels, reserving the cooking liquid. Remove mussels from shells and set aside. Discard the ones that haven't opened.\n  5. Strain the mussel cooking liquid through a fine sieve and place it in a saucepan.\n  6. Add the watercress broth, season with salt and pepper, and heat over medium-high heat until hot. Beat with an emulsion blender or whisk until frothy.\n\n### HALIBUT\n- **Ingredients:**\n  - 4 6-ounce skinless halibut fillets\n  - Kosher salt\n  - Freshly ground white pepper\n  - 2 tablespoons grapeseed or other neutral oil\n\n- **Instructions:**\n  1. Season the halibut liberally with salt and pepper.\n  2. Heat the oil in a large skillet over medium-high heat.\n  3. Add the halibut (skinned side up) and cook until browned and flaky, about 2–3 minutes per side.\n\n### TOPPING\n- **Ingredients:**\n  - 4 tablespoons pink lentils\n  - 1 tablespoon corn oil\n  - 2 tablespoons finely diced onions\n  - Kosher salt\n  - Freshly ground white pepper\n  - 4 breakfast (or other small) radishes, finely sliced\n\n(Note: The instructions for preparing the topping are not provided in the document.)\n\n--- \n\nThis format provides a clear and organized way to understand and follow the recipes in the document."
