    "source": "mcgee.pdf_page_190_full",
    "contenu": "### Extracted Content from Document:\n\n#### MEAT\n- **Cold-Smoking Meat**: \n  - **Method**: The meat undergoes cold-smoking, held at low temperatures (32°F/0°C but more usually between 60 and 80°F/15–25°C). Smoke vapors deposit onto the meat surface and develop flavors more slowly than in hot smoking. Cold-smoking allows for higher concentrations of sweet-spicy phenolic components, potentially more flavorsome but also accumulating possible carcinogens. The humidity and “wet” smoking methods impact the efficiency and strength of flavor infusion.\n  \n#### FERMENTED MEATS: CURED SAUSAGES\n- **General Process**: \n  - **Preparation**: Milk is transformed into long-keeping and flavorful cheese by removing some of its moisture, salting it, and encouraging non-harmful microbes to grow, thus increasing acidity.\n  - **Treatment**: Meat can be treated similarly, with processes like salting and re-forming different types of sausage. Fermented sausages develop intense flavors from benign bacteria breaking down proteins and fats into savory and aromatic molecules.\n  - **Historical Development**: Originating from prehistoric times, the method involved salting and drying meat scraps to preserve them. The tightly packed scraps allowed microbe-laden surfaces to develop into rich fermentation masses inside the moist mass.\n\n- **Specific Types and Styles**:\n  - **Southern and Northern:** \n    - Southern European style (e.g., Italian salami, Spanish and Portuguese chorizos) uses less water, more salt (>4%) and can be stored at room temperature.\n    - Northern European style (typical of northern Europe and German Cervelat) has higher water content (40-50%), about 3.5% salt, and needs refrigeration; both types can be eaten uncooked.\n\n- **Making Fermented Sausages**:\n  - **Ingredients**: Mix of meat, fat, bacteria culture (using nitrates or nitrites), salt, and spices with some sugar.\n  - **Fermentation**: The bacteria transform the lactose in the meat into lactic acid over 18 hours to three days at temperatures between 60-100°F/15-38°C. This increases sausage acidity to around pH 4.5-5, which helps prevent spoilage.\n  - **Aging**: Fermentation is followed by aging during which sugar aldehydes and fruity esters develop, enhancing the flavor further. The final steps typically involve cooking, smoking, and drying to achieve the desired moisture and tenderness.\n  - **Spoilage Prevention**: White mold coats (e.g., Penicillium, Candida, Debaryomyces) develop on the casing during drying, adding to flavor and protecting against spoilage microbes.\n\nThis document delves into detailed methods and practices related to meat processing, particularly focusing on cold-smoking and fermented sausages, elucidating the intricate balance of flavors, humidity, temperature, and microbial activities involved in these traditional meat preservation techniques."
  },
