    "source": "dokumen.pub_daring-pairings-a-master-sommelier-matches-distinctive-wines-with-recipes-from-his-favorite-chefs-9780520945562.pdf_page_227",
    "contenu": "Certainly! Below is the structured content of the text extracted from the document:\n\n### Where It's Grown\n- **Countries**: Algeria, Argentina, Australia (South Australia: Barossa Valley), Chile, France (Languedoc-Roussillon: Aude, Banyuls, Corbières, Hérault, Minervois), Israel, Mexico, Morocco, Spain (Catalonia: Priorat; Rioja), Tunisia, Uruguay, U.S.A. (California: Central Valley [Lodi], Sonoma County [Alexander Valley, Dry Creek Valley], Mendocino County, Texas)\n\n### Description\n- **Carignan** is described as the workhorse grape of southwestern France's Languedoc-Roussillon, which is the most productive winemaking region. It is primarily used for basic table wine or distilled for industrial purposes. Its ability in blending, due to acidity, tannins, and pigment, makes it ideal for producing Carignan-based red wines.\n\n### Regional Notes\n- **Spain**: Known locally as Cariñena or Mazuelo. It is used to add complexity and provides a potent, spicy, and floral character. It is distinguished particularly in the Priorat region.\n- **France**: The best varietal efforts are noted as concentrated and full of peppery spice, found mainly in Minervois, Collioure, and Fitou. Carignan blends well with Grenache in regions like Banyuls and near Collioure.\n- **Italy**: Celebrated for its blends with Carignano in Sardinia, notably offering a rustic quality with notes of plum and black olive.\n- **Algeria & Tunisia**: Frequently found in blends, reputed to be quite tasty.\n- **USA**: In California, Carignan thrives particularly in Lodi, Alexander Valley, and Dry Creek Valley in Sonoma County, and Mendocino. Noted for its deep plum nines and sharp acidity.\n\n### Tasting Notes\n- Carignan wines are known for their peppery spice and may have notes of plum and black olive. They typically present a rustic quality with a fruit style that can range from desiccated and pruny to quietly potent.\n  \n### Commentary\n- The author expresses a personal preference for Carignan wines from Lodi, praising its deep plum notes and pointed acidity. He suggests that Carignan, despite often being underappreciated, plays an important but minor role in the wine regions it inhabits, contributing to more interesting and complex wines."
