    "contenu": "The document discusses various aspects of the Roussanne grape variety, highlighting its use and characteristics in different wine regions.\n\n---\n\n**Roussanne Wine Profile:**\n\n1. **Regional Variations:**\n   - **Northern Rhône, France:** Used in red wines like Hermitage and white wines such as St.-Joseph and Crozes-Hermitage. Noted for rich and exotic aromatics resembling chamomile tea, fresh herbs, and bitter citrus peel.\n   - **Southern Rhône, France:** Key component in Châteauneuf-du-Pape whites, adding unique perfume. Occasionally bottled locally as a varietal wine.\n   - **Provence, France:** Produces a specific clone named Roussanne du Var, noted for deeper straw yellow hue. Differentiated from Provençal grape Rousette.\n   - **Savoie, France:** Known as Bergeron, adds intrigue to local white wine blends.\n   - **Italy:** Grown in Liguria and blended with Trebbiano in the Montecarlo Bianco. Also a part of a white Rhône-style blend.\n   - **Australia:** Performs well in Victoria, maintaining a varietal wine production and part of white Rhône-style blends.\n\n2. **Vintner’s Choices:**\n   - **Oak Usage:** Occasionally vinified in older oak barrels, especially in Châteauneuf-du-Pape, to emphasize unique personality.\n   - **Blending:** Often blended with Marsanne. New World producers are experimenting with blends including Viognier and Chardonnay, aiming for food-friendly and aromatic profiles.\n\n3. **Tasting Notes:**\n   - Provides a complex and enchanting aroma to wines, enhancing textures and adding a distinct personality that is appreciated both in younger and older wines.\n\n---\n\nThis summary captures the geographical distribution of Roussanne, its contributions to wine character and flavor, and the winemaking choices that influence its expression."
